 attempted to understand how the program worked. As she traveled from site to site with the two female state employees who implemented the program's policies, she saw that program practices reproduced middle-class values rather than female solidarity. In spite of this, she argues for the potential of female professional power, with implications for democracy and social justice. Perhaps most interesting of all, Byrnes portrays the formation of nonborder maquilas in rich detail and shows how government employees at the local level personally engage in "driving the state."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aEmigrant remittanceszMexicozGuanajuato (State) 0aEmigrant remittanceszMexicozGuanajuato (State). 0aJob creationxGovernment policyzMexicozGuanajuato (State) 0aJob creationxGovernment policyzMexicozGuanajuato (State). 0aWomen offshore assembly industry workersxServices forzMexicozGuanajuato (State) 0aWomen offshore assembly industry workersxServices forzMexicozGuanajuato (State). 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501722462.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG